e = Victoria Gonzales Heights | work = Canadian Climate Normals 1971\u20132000 | accessdate = 29 April 2016}}</ref> || 22/11 || 71/51 || 7/1 || 44/33\n|-\n|}\n\n== Politics ==\n=== Federal politics ===\nIn Canadian politics, the term \"the West\" is used misleadingly in Canadian media style guides as shorthand for the [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative]] leanings of Western Canadians, as contrasted with the greater likelihood for candidates from either the [[Liberal Party of Canada]] or the [[New Democratic Party of Canada|New Democratic Party]] (NDP) to be elected in [[Central Canada]]{{Citation needed|date=June 2015}}. Exceptions exist, particularly in British Columbia, as well as in the prairie city of Winnipeg, and where the Liberal Party hold seats. The [[social democracy|social democratic]] NDP had its origins on the Canadian Prairies and in the mining and pulp mill towns and railway camps of British Columbia and has a history of support in Manitoba and British Columbia.\n\nThe western provinces are represented in the [[Parliament of Canada]] by 104 [[Member of Parliament|Members of Parliament]] (MPs) in the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] (British Columbia 42, Alberta 34, Saskatchewan and Manitoba 14 each) and 24 senators (6 from each province). Currently, of the 104 western MPs in the Commons, 71 are Conservatives, the New Democrats and Liberals have 15 seats respectively, 2 are Green, and one independent.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|+2019 Federal Election Results for Western Canada\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"|Party name\n! [[British Columbia|BC]]\n! [[Alberta|AB]]\n! [[Saskatchewan|SK]]\n! [[Manitoba|MB]]\n! Total\n|-\n|{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|background}} rowspan=\"2\" |&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" rowspan=\"2\"|[[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|Seats:\n| 11\n| -\n| -\n| 4\n| 15\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|Vote:\n| 26.1\n| 13.7\n| 11.6\n| 