pper_house            = \n| lower_house            = \n| unit_pref              = Metric\n<!-- ALL fields with measurements have automatic unit conversion -->\n<!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| area_footnotes         = <ref name=StatCan2011>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table-Tableau.cfm?LANG=Eng&T=101&S=50&O=A|title=Population and Dwelling Count Highlight Tables, 2011 Census|date=2019-06-03|df=dmy|series=Population and dwelling counts|publisher=[[Statistics Canada]]|location=Ottawa|access-date=2012-03-17|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/qTB8e|archive-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n| area_urban_footnotes   = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_rural_footnotes   = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_metro_footnotes   = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_magnitude         = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_note              = \n| area_water_percent     = \n| area_rank              = \n| area_blank1_title      = \n| area_blank2_title      = \n<!-- square kilometers -->\n| area_total_km2         = 2703159\n| area_land_km2          = \n| area_water_km2         = \n| area_urban_km2         = \n| area_rural_km2         = \n| area_metro_km2         = \n| area_blank1_km2        = \n| area_blank2_km2        = \n<!-- hectares -->\n| area_total_ha          = \n| area_land_ha           = \n| area_water_ha          = \n| area_urban_ha          = \n| area_rural_ha          = \n| area_metro_ha          = \n| area_blank1_ha         = \n| area_blank2_ha         = \n| length_km              = \n| width_km               = \n| dimensions_footnotes   = \n| elevation_footnotes    = \n| elevation_m            = \n| population_as_of       = 2016\n| population_footnotes   = <ref name=2016censusPs&Ts/>\n| population_total       = 11091947\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| population_note        = \n| population_demonym     = \n| timezone1              = \n| utc_offset1            = \n| timezone1_DST          = \n| utc_offset1_DST        = \n| postal_code_type       = \n| postal_code            = \n| area_code_type         = \n| area_code              = \n| iso_code               = \n| website                = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Western Canada''', also referred to as the '''Western provinces''' and more commonly known as '''the West''', is a [[list of regions of Canada|region]] of [[Canada]] that includes the four [[provinces and territories of Canada|provinces]] of [[Alberta]], [[British Columbia]], [[Manitoba]], and [[Saskatchewan]].<ref name=2011censussummary>{{cite web | url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/as-sa/98-310-x/98-310-x2011001-eng.pdf | title=The Canadian Population in 2011: Population Counts and Growth | publisher=[[Statistics Canada]] | type=[[PDF]] | isbn=978-1-100-19962-7 | date=February 2012 | accessdate=December 27, 2014}}</ref> British Columbia is culturally, economically, geographically, and politically distinct from the other parts of Western Canada and is often referred to as the \"[[British Columbia Coast|west coast]]\" or \"Pacific Canada\",{{cn|date=September 2019}} while Alberta, Saskatchewan, and Manitoba are sometimes grouped together as the [[Canadian Prairies|Prairie Provinces]] and most commonly known as \"The Prairies\".{{clear left}}\n\n== Capital cities ==\nThe capital cities of the four western provinces, from west to east, are [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]] (British Columbia), [[Edmonton]] (Alberta), [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]] (Saskatchewan) and [[Winnipeg]] (Manitoba). With the exception of Winnipeg, which is the largest city in Manitoba, all other provincial capitals of the Western Provinces are located in the second-largest metropolitan areas of their respective province.\n\n== Constitutional history ==\n{{main|Constitutional history of Canada}}\nWestern Canada is the traditional territory of numerous First Nations predating the arrival of Europeans. As Britain colonized the west, it established treaties with various First Nations, took control of other areas without opposition and fought with other First Nations to take control of Western Canada. Not all lands were ceded by the First Nations to British control and land claims are still ongoing.\n\nIn 1858, the British government established the [[Colony of British Columbia (1858\u20131866)|Colony of British Columbia]], governing that part of Canada still known as British Columbia. The British government also established the Hudson's Bay Company which controlled most of the current area of Western Canada, northern Ontario and northern Quebec, the area known as [[Rupert's Land]] and the [[North-Western Territory]]. In 1870, the British government transferred the lands of the company to Canada. The area of Western Canada not within British Columbia was established as the [[Northwest Territories]] under Canadian control. The Western Canadian provinces other than British Columbia were established from areas of the Northwest Territories:\n\n*[[Manitoba]] established as a province of Canada in 1870, following the enacting of the ''[[Manitoba Act]]''.<ref name=\"Dodek2013\">{{cite book|author=Adam Dodek|title=The Canadian Constitution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SE-k3CGNaW4C&pg=PA19|year=2013|publisher=Dundurn|isbn=978-1-4597-0932-4|page=19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kennedy|first1=W.P.M|title=Statutes, treaties and documents of the Canadian Constitution, 1713- 1929|url=http://eco.canadiana.ca/view/oocihm.9_03428/669?r=0&s=1|website=Early Canadiana Online|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>\n*[[British Columbia]]: Under terms that Canada would absorb the colony's debt, would begin to subsidize public work, and would begin to construct a railway allowing travel from British Columbia to [[Ontario]], British Columbia agreed to join [[Canadian confederation]] in 1871.<ref name=\"Dodek2013\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=British Columbia|url=http://www.canadiana.ca/citm/themes/constitution/constitution14_e.html#bc|website=Canada in the Making: Constitutional History|publisher=Early Canadiana Online|accessdate=10 February 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150516013056/http://www.canadiana.ca/citm/themes/constitution/constitution14_e.html#bc|archivedate=16 May 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Saskatchewan]]: Established as province in 1905, with the implementation of the ''[[Saskatchewan Act]]''.<ref name=\"Dodek2013\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Saskatchewan|url=http://thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/saskatchewan/|website=The Canadian Encyclopedia|publisher=Historica Canada|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Alberta]]: In 1905, the same year as Saskatchewan, Alberta also was established as province. Just like Saskatchewan had the ''Saskatchewan Act'', Alberta had the ''[[Alberta Act]]''.<ref name=\"Dodek2013\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=1867-1931: Canada in the Making|url=http://www.canadiana.ca/citm/themes/constitution/constitution14_e.html#alberta|website=Canada in the Making: Constitutional History|publisher=Early Canadiana Online|accessdate=10 February 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150516013056/http://www.canadiana.ca/citm/themes/constitution/constitution14_e.html#alberta|archivedate=16 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n[[File:Calgary Skyline May 2018.jpg|thumb|Calgary is the largest [[municipality]] by population in western Canada.|454x454px]]\nAs of the [[Canada 2016 Census|2016 Census]], the total population of Western Canada was nearly 11.1 million, including approximately 4.65 million in British Columbia, 4.07 million in Alberta, 1.1 million in Saskatchewan, and 1.28 million in Manitoba.<ref name=2016censusPs&Ts>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/index.cfm?Lang=E| title=Census Profile, for Canada, provinces and territories, 2016 censuses | publisher=Statistics Canada | date=2017-02-08 | accessdate=2012-02-11}}</ref> This represents 31.5% of Canada's population.<ref name=2011censussummary/> While [[Vancouver]] serves as the largest metropolitan area in Western Canada at nearly 2.5 million people,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table.cfm?Lang=Eng&T=205&S=3&RPP=100 | title=Population and dwelling counts, for census metropolitan areas, 2016 and 2011 censuses | publisher=Statistics Canada | date=February 2018 | accessdate=2018-06-05}}</ref> [[Calgary]] serves as the largest municipality at over 1.2 million people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table.cfm?Lang=Eng&T=302&SR=1&S=86&O=A&RPP=9999&PR=48|title=Population and dwelling counts, for Canada, provinces and territories, and census subdivisions (municipalities), 2016 and 2011 censuses \u2013 100% data|publisher=[[Statistics Canada]]|date=February 2018|accessdate=2018-06-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Census metropolitan areas ===\n[[File:Vancouver aerial view.jpg|thumb|Vancouver is the largest [[census metropolitan area]] by population in western Canada.|174x174px]]\n[[File:Downtown edmonton.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|View of Edmonton's [[central business district]] in 2018]]\n[[File:Downtown Area, Winnipeg - panoramio (1).jpg|thumb|Centred on the intersection of [[Portage and Main]], [[Downtown Winnipeg]] is the city's [[central business district]].]]\nAs of the 2016 Census, [[Statistics Canada]] recognized ten [[census metropolitan area]]s within Western Canada, including four in British Columbia, three in Alberta, two in Saskatchewan, and one in Manitoba.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table.cfm?Lang=Eng&T=201&S=3&O=D|title=Population and dwelling counts, for Canada and census subdivisions (municipalities), 2016 and 2011 censuses|publisher=[[Statistics Canada]]|date=February 2018|accessdate=2018-06-05}}</ref> The following is a list of these areas and their populations as of 2016.\n\nFrom 2011 to 2016, the fastest growing CMAs in the country were the five located in Alberta and Saskatchewan: [[Calgary]] (+14.6%), [[Edmonton]] (+13.9%), [[Saskatoon]] (+12.5%), [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]] (+11.8%) and [[Lethbridge]] (+10.8%). These were the only CMAs in the country to register growth over 10%. The three fastest growing CMAs - Calgary, Edmonton, and Saskatoon - were unchanged from the previous intercensal period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statcan.gc.ca/daily-quotidien/170208/dq170208a-eng.htm|title=The Daily \u2014 Population size and growth in Canada: Key results from the 2016 Census|first=Government of Canada, Statistics|last=Canada|website=www.statcan.gc.ca|accessdate=29 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170210133245/http://www.statcan.gc.ca/daily-quotidien/170208/dq170208a-eng.htm|archivedate=10 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:35%\"\n!  width=\"*\" |Name\n!  width=\"*\" |Population<br />(2016)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table.cfm?Lang=Eng&T=201&S=3&O=D|title=Population and dwelling counts, for Canada and census subdivisions (municipalities), 2016 and 2011 censuses|publisher=[[Statistics Canada]]|date=February 2018|accessdate=2018-06-05}}</ref>\n!  width=\"*\" |National<br />rank<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table.cfm?Lang=Eng&T=201&S=3&O=D|title=Population and dwelling counts, for Canada and census subdivisions (municipalities), 2016 and 2011 censuses|publisher=[[Statistics Canada]]|date=February 2018|accessdate=2018-06-05}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Vancouver]] ||align=center| {{nts|2,463,431}} ||align=center| 3\n|-\n|[[Calgary]] ||align=center| {{nts|1,392,609}} ||align=center| 4\n|-\n|[[Edmonton]] ||align=center| {{nts|1,321,426}} ||align=center| 6\n|-\n|[[Winnipeg]] ||align=center| {{nts|778,489}} ||align=center| 8\n|-\n|[[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]] ||align=center| {{nts|367,770}} ||align=center| 15\n|-\n|[[Saskatoon]] ||align=center| {{nts|295,095}} ||align=center| 17\n|-\n|[[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]] ||align=center| {{nts|236,481}} ||align=center| 18\n|-\n|[[Kelowna]] ||align=center| {{nts|194,882}} ||align=center| 22\n|-\n|[[Abbotsford, British Columbia|Abbotsford]]\u2013[[Mission, British Columbia|Mission]] ||align=center| {{nts|180,518}} ||align=center| 23\n|-\n|[[Lethbridge]] ||align=center| {{nts|117,394}} ||align=center| 34\n|-\n|}\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:Val marie southside badlands.jpg|thumb|Badlands in Southern Saskatchewan]]\nWestern Canada consists of the country's four westernmost provinces: British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan and Manitoba. It covers 2.9 million square kilometres \u2013 almost 29% of Canada's land area. British Columbia adjoins the [[Pacific Ocean]] to the west, while Manitoba has a coastline on [[Hudson Bay]] in its northeast of the province. Both Alberta and Saskatchewan are [[landlocked]] between British Columbia and Manitoba.\n\nThe [[Canadian Prairies]] are part of a vast [[sedimentary]] [[Great Plains|plain]] covering much of [[Alberta]], southern Saskatchewan, and southwestern Manitoba. The prairies form a significant portion of the land area of Western Canada. The plains generally describes the expanses of largely flat, arable agricultural land which sustain extensive grain farming operations in the southern part of the provinces. Despite this, some areas such as the [[Cypress Hills (Canada)|Cypress Hills]] and Alberta Badlands are quite hilly and the prairie provinces contain large areas of forest such as the [[Mid-Continental Canadian forests]].\n\nIn Alberta and British Columbia, the [[Canadian Cordillera]] is bounded by the Rocky Mountains to the east and the [[Pacific Ocean]] to the west.\n\nThe [[Canadian Rockies]] are part of a major [[continental divide]] that extends north and south through western North America and western [[South America]]. The continental divide also defines much of the border between Alberta and British Columbia. The [[Columbia River|Columbia]] and the [[Fraser River]]s have their headwaters in the Canadian Rockies and are the second- and third-largest rivers, respectively, to drain to the west coast of North America. To the west of their headwaters, across the [[Rocky Mountain Trench]], is a second belt of mountains, the [[Columbia Mountains]], comprising the [[Selkirk Mountains|Selkirk]], [[Purcell Mountains|Purcell]], [[Monashee Mountains|Monashee]] and [[Cariboo Mountains]] sub-ranges.\n\n{{wide image|Peyto Lake Panorama.jpg|800px|[[Peyto Lake]] in Banff National Park, Alberta}}\n\n=== Climate ===\n[[File:Western Canada K\u00f6ppen.svg|400px|thumb|[[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen climate types]] in Western Canada]]\nThe [[British Columbia Coast|coast of British Columbia]] enjoys a moderate [[oceanic climate]] because of the influence of the Pacific Ocean, with temperatures similar to those of the [[British Isles]] (though Vancouver receives more precipitation than London and most of the Coast is much wetter).{{citation needed|date=December 2011}} Winters are typically wet and summers relatively dry. These areas enjoy the mildest winter weather in all of Canada, as temperatures rarely fall much below the freezing mark. The mountainous Interior of the province is drier and has colder winters, but experiences hotter summers than the more moderate coastal areas. [[Lytton, British Columbia]], a small town that sits at the confluence of the Thompson River and Fraser River recorded the second-hottest temperature in Canada at {{convert|44.4|C}} observed on July 16 and 17 1941,<ref>[http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climateData/dailydata_e.html?timeframe=2&Prov=&StationID=966&Year=1941&Month=7&Day=26 Daily Data Report for July 1941]</ref> and is regularly referred as Canada's hot spot in summer with temperatures easily reaching the mid to high 30&nbsp;\u00b0C 's (upper 90s to low 100s&nbsp;\u00b0F) in July and August and sometimes top {{convert|40|C}}.\n\nAlberta has a dry continental climate with warm summers and cold winters. The province is open to cold Arctic weather systems from the north, which often produce extremely cold conditions in winter. Winters are generally quite cold, though some areas can experience a phenomenon known as the \"[[Chinook wind]],\" wherein warm winds raise the winter temperatures temporarily. In contrast, summers can fluctuate from cool to hot and are generally wetter.\n\n[[Saskatchewan]] and [[Manitoba]] have a continental climate and experience extremes in weather. Winters in both provinces can be classified as harsh with [[Arctic]] winds and {{convert|\u221240|C}} temperatures possible. Winter temperatures in both provinces average between {{convert|\u221210|and|\u221215|C}}. In contrast, summers can be hot with temperatures exceeding {{convert|35|C}} at least once per year in most locations. The hottest temperature ever recorded in Canada was {{convert|45|C}}, observed in 1937 at the weather stations of [[Yellow Grass, Saskatchewan]] and neighbouring [[Midale]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:60%; font-size:95%;\"\n|+'''Average daily maximum and minimum temperatures for 7 largest cities in Western Canada'''\n|-\n!City\n!July (\u00b0C)\n!July (\u00b0F)\n!January (\u00b0C)\n!January (\u00b0F)\n|-\n| [[Calgary]]<ref name=\"ccncalgary\">{{cite web |url= http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_1981_2010_e.html?stnID=2205&lang=e&dCode=1&province=ALTA&provBut=Go&month1=0&month2=12 |title= Calgary International Airport |work= Canadian Climate Normals 1981\u20132010 |publisher= [[Environment Canada]] |accessdate=May 8, 2014 }}</ref> || 23/9 || 73/48 || {{sort|2715|\u22121/\u221213}} || {{sort|5735|27/5}}\n|-\n| [[Edmonton]]<ref name=\"ccnedmonton\">{{cite web | title = Edmonton City Centre Airport | work = Canadian Climate Normals 1981\u22122010 | publisher = Environment Canada | date = August 19, 2013 | url = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_1981_2010_e.html?stnID=1867&lang=e&dCode=0&province=ALTA&provBut=Go&month1=0&month2=12 | accessdate = September 10, 2013}}</ref> || 23/12 || 73/54 || {{sort|2213|\u22126/\u221214}} || {{sort|4831|21/5}}\n|-\n| [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]]<ref name=\"ccnregina\">{{cite web | publisher = [[Environment Canada]] | url = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_1981_2010_e.html?stnID=3002&lang=e&dCode=1&province=SASK&provBut=Go&month1=0&month2=12 | title = Regina International Airport | work = Canadian Climate Normals 1981\u20132010 | accessdate = 12 May 2014}}</ref> || 26/11 || 79/52 || -10/-22 || 14/-8\n|-\n| [[Saskatoon]]<ref name=\"ccnsaskatoon\">{{cite web | publisher = [[Environment Canada]] | url = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_1981_2010_e.html?stnID=3328&lang=e&dCode=1&province=SASK&provBut=Go&month1=0&month2=12 | title = Saskatoon Diefenbaker International Airport | work = Canadian Climate Normals 1981\u20132010 | accessdate = May 12, 2014}}</ref> || 25/11 || 77/52 || -12/-22 || 10/-8\n|-\n| [[Winnipeg]]<ref name=\"ccnwinnipeg\">{{cite web | publisher = [[Environment Canada]] | url = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_1981_2010_e.html?stnID=3698&lang=e&dCode=1&province=MAN&provBut=Go&month1=0&month2=12 | title = Winnipeg Richardson International Airport | work = Canadian Climate Normals 1981\u20132010 | accessdate = May 7, 2014}}</ref> || 26/13 || 79/55 || \u221213/\u221220 || 9/\u22124\n|-\n| [[Vancouver]]<ref name =\"ccnvancouver\">{{cite web | url=http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_1981_2010_e.html?stnID=889&lang=e&StationName=Vancouver&SearchType=Contains&stnNameSubmit=go&dCode=1 | title=1981 to 2010 Canadian Climate Normals | publisher=Environment Canada | id = Climate ID: 1108447 | date=2015-09-22 | accessdate=2016-05-09}}</ref> || 22/13 || 71/54 || 6/1 || 43/33\n|-\n| [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]]<ref name=\"ccnvictoria\">{{cite web | publisher = Environment Canada | url = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_e.html?stnID=113&lang=e&province=BC&provSubmit=go&page=276&dCode=0 | title = Victoria Gonzales Heights | work = Canadian Climate Normals 1971\u20132000 | accessdate = 29 April 2016}}</ref> || 22/11 || 71/51 || 7/1 || 44/33\n|-\n|}\n\n== Politics ==\n=== Federal politics ===\nIn Canadian politics, the term \"the West\" is used misleadingly in Canadian media style guides as shorthand for the [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative]] leanings of Western Canadians, as contrasted with the greater likelihood for candidates from either the [[Liberal Party of Canada]] or the [[New Democratic Party of Canada|New Democratic Party]] (NDP) to be elected in [[Central Canada]]{{Citation needed|date=June 2015}}. Exceptions exist, particularly in British Columbia, as well as in the prairie city of Winnipeg, and where the Liberal Party hold seats. The [[social democracy|social democratic]] NDP had its origins on the Canadian Prairies and in the mining and pulp mill towns and railway camps of British Columbia and has a history of support in Manitoba and British Columbia.\n\nThe western provinces are represented in the [[Parliament of Canada]] by 104 [[Member of Parliament|Members of Parliament]] (MPs) in the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] (British Columbia 42, Alberta 34, Saskatchewan and Manitoba 14 each) and 24 senators (6 from each province). Currently, of the 104 western MPs in the Commons, 71 are Conservatives, the New Democrats and Liberals have 15 seats respectively, 2 are Green, and one independent.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|+2019 Federal Election Results for Western Canada\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"|Party name\n! [[British Columbia|BC]]\n! [[Alberta|AB]]\n! [[Saskatchewan|SK]]\n! [[Manitoba|MB]]\n! Total\n|-\n|{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|background}} rowspan=\"2\" |&nbsp;&nbsp