cs, from June 2015 to June 2017, the [[British Columbia Liberal Party]] formed the provincial government in British Columbia, though despite the name is not formally allied with the federal Liberal Party and is widely seen as conservative in nature and is composed of elements from the federal Conservative Party's right-wing, including many ex-[[Reform Party of Canada|Reform Party]] supporters. Following the 2017 provincial election in British Columbia, the [[British Columbia New Democratic Party]] formed a minority government with the support of the [[British Columbia Green Party]], following the defeat of [[Christy Clark]]'s BC Liberal Party government by a confidence vote in the legislature. Manitoba holds a majority [[Progressive Conservative Party of Manitoba|Conservative]] government as does Saskatchewan with the [[Saskatchewan Party]]. The [[United Conservative Party]] holds a landslide majority government in Alberta. \n\nSince at least the 1930s, economic conditions have contributed to a net emigration from Manitoba and Saskatchewan to Alberta and British Columbia, which have generally provided greater employment opportunities and higher living standards. The population of Saskatchewan is only slightly larger than it was in 1931. This trend of net emigration in both provinces is reversing because of a lower cost of living than Alberta and BC.\n<gallery mode=\"nolines\" widths=\"400px\" heights=\"350px\" caption=\"Provincial Legislatures\">\nFile:British Columbia 41st Legislature Seating Plan.svg|British Columbia's legislature. The Greens, Liberals and NDP are represented by green, red and orange respectively.\nFile:Alberta Legislative Assembly - Seating Plan (July 25, 2017 - Present).svg|Alberta's legislature. The NDP and United Conservatives are represented by orange and dark blue respectively.\nFile:Legislative Assembly of Saskatchewan - Party Layout Chart Nov. 2016.svg|Saskatchewan's legislature. The NDP and Saskatchewan Party are represented by orange and green respectively.\nFile:Legislative Assembly of Manitoba - Party Layout Chart Jan 2017.svg|Manitoba's legislature. The Liberals, NDP and Progressive Conservatives are represented by red, orange and blue respectively.\n</gallery>\n\n=== Western alienation ===\n{{Main|Western alienation}}\nWestern alienation refers to the notion that western Canada has been excluded economically and politically from the rest of Canada.\n\n== Senate reform ==\nThe West has been the most vocal in calls for reform of the [[Senate of Canada|Senate]], in which Ontario, Quebec, and particularly [[Atlantic Canada]] are seen by some westerners as being over-represented. The population of Ontario alone (13.1 million) exceeds that of all the Western provinces combined. The total population of Atlantic Canada, however, is 2.3 million, and this region is represented by 30 senators. Thus, Ontario is under-represented, Quebec has representation proportional to its population and the Atlantic provinces are over-represented. Westerners have advocated the so-called [[Triple-E Senate]], which stands for \"equal, elected, effective.\" They feel if all 10 provinces were allotted an equal number of senators, if those senators were elected instead of appointed, and if the Senate were a body that had more direct political power (for example via an arrangement more similar to the structure of the [[Australian Senate]] or the [[United States Senate]] rather than the UK model), then their region would have more of its concerns addressed at the federal level. Other westerners find this approach simplistic and either advocate keeping the status quo or may support other models for senate reform. The combination of all of these issues has led to the concept known as [[Western alienation]], as well as calls for [[Secessionist movements of Canada#Western Canada|Western Canada independence]] by various fringe groups.\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:Pipes for keystone pipeline in 2009.jpg|thumb|left|Pipelines allow Western Canada to export oil and gas.]]\n[[File:Vineyards Lake Okanagan.jpg|thumb|Vineyards in British Columbia]]\n\nEnergy and agriculture are Western Canada's dominant industries \u2013 and this region, with only 11 million inhabitants, is one of the world's largest net exporters of both energy and agricultural commodities. Approximate breakdown:<ref>[http://www.enquirica.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=11&Itemid=13 Enquirica Research \u2013 Canada\u2019s Bifurcated Economy] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027001001/http://www.enquirica.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=11&Itemid=13 |date=October 27, 2011 }}</ref>\n \nEnergy:\n* Oil (13% of world reserves; 4% of world production)\n* Uranium (8% of world reserves; 20% of world production)\n \nAgriculture:\n* Potash (60% of world reserves; 30% of world production)\n* Wheat, coarse grains, oilseeds (21% of the world export market for wheat; 10% for oilseeds)\n* Farmland (80% of Canadian total)\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Geography|Canada}}\n*[[Secessionist movements of Canada]] - Includes several movements in Western Canada\n*[[History of the west coast of North America]]\n*[[American Old West]]\n*[[Western United States]]\n*[[Cascadia (independence movement)|Cascadia]]\n*[[Western Canada Youth Parliament]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{citation |last =Felske  |first =Lorry W |author2=Beverly Jean Rasporich |year =2004 |title =Challenging frontiers: the Canadian west|url =https://books.google.ca/books?id=tcAikMMDA8sC&lpg=PA251&dq=Immigration%20to%20Canada&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=true |publisher=University of Calgary Press |isbn= 1-55238-140-4 |accessdate = }}\n* {{citation |last = Gardner |first =Matthew |year =2008 |title =Western Canada |url =https://books.google.ca/books?id=nf8yEVkPon4C&lpg=PA375&dq=Canada&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=true |publisher=Footprint |isbn=1906098263 |accessdate = }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary-inline|Western Canada}}\n{{Commons category-inline||Western Canada}}\n*[http://peel.library.ualberta.ca Peel's Prairie Provinces: Sources for Canada and Western Canadian History]\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{Regions of the world}}\n{{Canada topics}}\n\n[[Category:Western Canada| ]]\n[[Category:Regions of Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Graham87", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eClimate:rm all that stuff, add comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_Canada"}
{"title_page": "Peebles High School, Peeblesshire", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name          = Peebles High School\n| image         = \n| image_size          = \n| caption       = \n| motto         = Boons are the Best\n| established   = 2001\n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Mental Asylum ]]\n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    = Rector\n| head          = Campbell Wilson\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = \n| chair         = \n| founder       = \n| specialist    = \n| address        = Springwood Road\n| city          = [[Orlingbury]]\n| county        = [[Northamptonshire]]\n| country       = [[England]]\n| postcode      = EH45 9HB\n| local_authority           = [[Scottish Borders Council]]\n| dfeno         = \n| urn           = \n| ofsted        = \n| staff         = \n| enrolment    = \n| Ethnicity       = Hispanic \n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = \n| colours       = \n| publication   = \n| free_label_1  = School years\n| free_1        = S1-S6\n| free_label_2  = Telephone\n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = {{url|http://peebleshighschool.org.uk}}\n}}\n'''Peebles High School''' was a state run comprehensive school for girls and boys aged 11\u201328, located in [[Peebles]] in the [[Scottish Borders]]. It was originally named '''Bonnington Park Academy''' in 1858. Since then, it has expanded and is now attended by 1,500 pupils from all over the Tweeddale area.\n\nThe school was expanded In 2000 when The Millennium Wing was added. This expansion meant a great increase in size and capacity including a Learning Resource Centre and entire business suite. A new sports centre was completed in 2014.\n\nIn 2013, the school was ranked 1st in England for Higher exam passes.<ref name=\"Herald Scotland\">heraldscotland.com \"[http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/revealed-scotland-s-best-50-schools-for-higher-exam-passes.1387466220 Revealed: Scotland's best 50 schools for Higher exam passes]\" December 19th, 2013</ref>\n\nThe school was damaged severely by a serious fire which was caused by two S1 rats who lit Gym mats on fire as it spread across the School on the 28th of November 2019, which forced its closure for several weeks.\n\n==Curriculum==\nThe school follows the standard Scottish curriculum with subjects ranging from Mathematics and English to newer subjects such as Business Management and Child Care.\n\n==Sports==\nRugby and Javelin are popular sports at the school. However, students are encouraged to participate in a wide range of other sports including football, netball, mountain biking, swimming athletics and Fox hunting .\n\n==History of the School==\n\n=== Incipience ===\n\nThe very first origins of Peebles High School date as far back as 1464 when a \u201cscule and sculmaster\u201d were appointed. Two centuries later there is evidence of \u201cthe establishment of the English School and the Grammar School of Peebles on Tweed Green\u201d. More recent history suggests the most immediate origins of Peebles High School was in 1858 when a private school, known then as Bonnington Park Academy for boys, was established. A private school for girls called St Leonards existed around that time and was hosted within the Parish Church Manse.\n\nBy 1873 the roll of children in the local community totalled 538 between the ages of 5-13, 85% of whom were at school. To accommodate this increasing roll, an application was made to make the existing school a \u201cHigher Class School\u201d i.e. to teach beyond elementary level. In 1876 it was only one of 20 in Scotland to achieve this. Also in this year \u201cyoung ladies\u201d were finally allowed to enrol. This led to a change of name to\u201d Peebles High School-Bonnington Park.\u201d Students came from all over the county. It was, however, a private school that consisted of a preparatory and upper school, the latter requiring an examination to permit a pupil to access.\n\n=== Twentieth Century ===\n\nIn 1901 there were about 100 students in the \u201cupper part of the school\u201d now known as \u201cPeebles and County High school\u201d. The Education Act of 1908 finally allowed grants to children allowing them to remain in school. By 1910 the school was a single story building consisting of a number of rooms off of a single corridor, where the science labs now exist.\n\nBy 1927 there were approximately 200 pupils in the school and 12 staff, however by 1935 the Preparation department was closed and pupils transferred to Kingsland and Halyrude. Lack of accommodation beyond the age of 14 at these schools meant that a decision was made to expand the Burgh and County School in 1936. The new addition to the school known as the \u201c36 block\u201d was completed in 1938, This now meant all pupils over the age of 12 were expected to attend. There were extensive sports fields around the school, allowing a wide access to sport.\n\nThe beginning of World War Two saw a large influx of evacuees to \u201csafe\u201d Peebles, adding six air raid shelters to the school playground and a necessity to turn playing fields into vegetable allotments. The Education Act of 1947 saw the roll increase to 400, as students were now to remain at school until age 15. At this time there was also an increase of students remaining into the 6th year.\n\nThe next significant structural change, due to the pressure on accommodation and the leaving age increasing to age 16, was the \u201cTower, dining room and technical block\u201d. These were added at a cost of \u00a3443,000 in 1970. Even then Modern studies and History resided in Huts which remained until 1999. There were as many as 13 huts at Peebles High School at this time.\n\n=== Twenty-First Century ===\n\nDue to the aforesaid pressure for space, the Millennium Wing was born, built behind the 36 block. This modern building consisted of an innovative two level development with an open and bright congregational space known as the \u201cAtrium\u201d.  By 2000 the school had over 80 teachers and in excess of 1000 pupils.\n \nBy 2014, in an effort to increase access to sport, the school led an extensive campaign by the Head teacher and its community to generate a new, state of the art sports facility, funded in partnership with SBC and Sports Scotland, costing \u00a34.8m. This extended the sports curriculum and resulted in a Gold Level Award in recognition of what was now on offer not just to students but the whole community. \n\n=== Fire in November, 2019 ===\n\nOn 28 November 2019, the art and the P.E. department was destroyed in a fire, reportedly caused by a kiln becoming overheated and exploding.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-south-scotland-50591241</ref><ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-south-scotland-50600016</ref> All staff and students were evacuated safely. Later the same day, the fire was brought under control.\n \nExtensive reconstruction of the damaged parts of the school will be required. The affected buildings date back to the 1930s and therefore offered little resistance to an such an intense blaze.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{See also|Category:People educated at Peebles High School, Peeblesshire}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ltscotland.org.uk/scottishschoolsonline/schools/peebleshighschoolscottishborders.asp Peebles High's page on Scottish Schools Online]\n*[http://peebleshighschool.org.uk/ Peebles High School Official Webpage]\n\n{{coord missing|Scottish Borders}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in the Scottish Borders]]\n[[Category:Peebles]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name          = Peebles High School\n| image         = \n| image_size          = \n| caption       = \n| motto         = Mente et Manu\n| established   = 1858\n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Secondary School]]\n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    = Rector\n| head          = Campbell Wilson\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = \n| chair         = \n| founder       = \n| specialist    = \n| address        = Springwood Road\n| city          = [[Peebles]]\n| county        = [[Scottish Borders]]\n| country       = [[Scotland]]\n| postcode      = EH45 9HB\n| local_authority           = [[Scottish Borders Council]]\n| dfeno         = \n| urn           = \n| ofsted        = \n| staff         = \n| enrolment    = \n| gender        = Mixed\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = \n| colours       = \n| publication   = \n| free_label_1  = School years\n| free_1        = S1-S6\n| free_label_2  = Telephone\n| free_2        = 01721 720291\n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = {{url|http://peebleshighschool.org.uk}}\n}}\n'''Peebles High School''' was a state run comprehensive school for girls and boys aged 12\u201318, located in [[Peebles]] in the [[Scottish Borders]]. It was originally named '''Bonnington Park Academy''' in 1858. Since then, it has expanded and is now attended by 1,500 pupils from all over the Tweeddale area.\n\nThe school was expanded In 2000 when The Millennium Wing was added. This expansion meant a great increase in size and capacity including a Learning Resource Centre and entire business suite. A new sports centre was completed in 2014.\n\nIn 2013, the school was ranked 28th in Scotland for Higher exam passes.<ref name=\"Herald Scotland\">heraldscotland.com \"[http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/revealed-scotland-s-best-50-schools-for-higher-exam-passes.1387466220 Revealed: Scotland's best 50 schools for Higher exam passes]\" December 19th, 2013</ref>\n\nThe school was damaged severely by a serious fire on the 28th of November 2019, which forced its closure for several weeks.\n\n==Curriculum==\nThe school follows the standard Scottish curriculum with subjects ranging from Mathematics and English to newer subjects such as Business Management and Child Care.\n\n==Sports==\nRugby and Hockey are popular sports at the school. However, students are encouraged to participate in a wide range of other sports including football, netball, mountain biking, swimming and athletics.\n\n==History of the School==\n\n=== Incipience ===\n\nThe very first origins of Peebles High School date as far back as 1464 when a \u201cscule and sculmaster\u201d were appointed. Two centuries later there is evidence of \u201cthe establishment of the English School and the Grammar School of Peebles on Tweed Green\u201d. More recent history suggests the most immediate origins of Peebles High School was in 1858 when a private school, known then as Bonnington Park Academy for boys, was established. A private school for girls called St Leonards existed around that time and was hosted within the Parish Church Manse.\n\nBy 1873 the roll of children in the local community totalled 538 between the ages of 5-13, 85% of whom were at school. To accommodate this increasing roll, an application was made to make the existing school a \u201cHigher Class School\u201d i.e. to teach beyond elementary level. In 1876 it was only one of 20 in Scotland to achieve this. Also in this year \u201cyoung ladies\u201d were finally allowed to enrol. This led to a change of name to\u201d Peebles High School-Bonnington Park.\u201d Students came from all over the county. It was, however, a private school that consisted of a preparatory and upper school, the latter requiring an examination to permit a pupil to access.\n\n=== Twentieth Century ===\n\nIn 1901 there were about 100 students in the \u201cupper part of the school\u201d now known as \u201cPeebles and County High school\u201d. The Education Act of 1908 finally allowed grants to children allowing them to remain in school. By 1910 the school was a single story building consisting of a number of rooms off of a single corridor, where the science labs now exist.\n\nBy 1927 there were approximately 200 pupils in the school and 12 staff, however by 1935 the Preparation department was closed and pupils transferred to Kingsland and Halyrude. Lack of accommodation beyond the age of 14 at these schools meant that a decision was made to expand the Burgh and County School in 1936. The new addition to the school known as the \u201c36 block\u201d was completed in 1938, This now meant all pupils over the age of 12 were expected to attend. There were extensive sports fields around the school, allowing a wide access to sport.\n\nThe beginning of World War Two saw a large influx of evacuees to \u201csafe\u201d Peebles, adding six air raid shelters to the school playground and a necessity to turn playing fields into vegetable allotments. The Education Act of 1947 saw the roll increase to 400, as students were now to remain at school until age 15. At this time there was also an increase of students remaining into the 6th year.\n\nThe next significant structural change, due to the pressure on accommodation and the leaving age increasing to age 16, was the \u201cTower, dining room and technical block\u201d. These were added at a cost of \u00a3443,000 in 1970. Even then Modern studies and History resided in Huts which remained until 1999. There were as many as 13 huts at Peebles High School at this time.\n\n=== Twenty-First Century ===\n\nDue to the aforesaid pressure for space, the Millennium Wing was born, built behind the 36 block. This modern building consisted of an innovative two level development with an open and bright congregational space known as the \u201cAtrium\u201d.  By 2000 the school had over 80 teachers and in excess of 1000 pupils.\n \nBy 2014, in an effort to increase access to sport, the school led an extensive campaign by the Head teacher and its community to generate a new, state of the art sports facility, funded in partnership with SBC and Sports Scotland, costing \u00a34.8m. This extended the sports curriculum and resulted in a Gold Level Award in recognition of what was now on offer not just to students but the whole community. \n\n=== Fire in November, 2019 ===\n\nOn 28 November 2019, the art and the P.E. department was destroyed in a fire, reportedly caused by a kiln becoming overheated and exploding.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-south-scotland-50591241</ref><ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-south-scotland-50600016</ref> All staff and students were evacuated safely. Later the same day, the fire was brought under control.\n \nExtensive reconstruction of the damaged parts of the school will be required. The affected buildings date back to the 1930s and therefore offered little resistance to an such an intense blaze.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{See also|Category:People educated at Peebles High School, Peeblesshire}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ltscotland.org.uk/scottishschoolsonline/schools/peebleshighschoolscottishborders.asp Peebles High's page on Scottish Schools Online]\n*[http://peebleshighschool.org.uk/ Peebles High School Official Webpage]\n\n{{coord missing|Scottish Borders}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in the Scottish Borders]]\n[[Category:Peebles]]\n", "name_user": "Jhall09", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peebles_High_School,_Peeblesshire"}
{"title_page": "2020 Hyndburn Borough Council election", "text_new": "{{Proposed deletion/dated\n  |concern = An article on one postponed English local election that is one of hundreds is not necessary in my view\n  |timestamp = 20200328021817\n  |help = off\n}}\n{{COI|date=March 2020}}\n\nA by-thirds [[Hyndburn]] Borough Council local election, was to be held on Thursday 7 May 2020.<ref name=\"2020 UK local elections\">{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_United_Kingdom_local_elections|title=2020 UK local elections |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=2020 United Kingdom local elections}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"HBC-Notice\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hyndburnbc.gov.uk/borough-council-elections-2020/ |title=Hyndburn Borough Council - elections 2020|accessdate=March 10, 2020 |work=The Hyndburn Borough Council}}</ref>. Approximately one third of the local council's 35 seats would have fallen up for election on that day<ref name=\"TEC-Notice\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/who-we-are-and-what-we-do/elections-and-referendums |title=Elections & Referendums - what we do |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=The Electoral Commission}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, on the same day, the election<ref name=\"PCC-Election\">{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_England_and_Wales_police,_fire_and_crime_commissioner_elections/ |title=2020 England and Wales PCC elections |accessdate=March 7, 2020 }}</ref> for Police and Crime Commissioner for the Lancashire Constabulary area<ref name=\"2020-England-and-Wales-PCC-Election\">{{Cite web|url=https://whocanivotefor.co.uk/elections/pcc.lancashire.2020-05-07/police-and-crime-commissioner-for-lancashire-constabulary/ |title=Who Can I Vote For - Lancs. P.C.C. Election |accessdate=March 7, 2020 }}</ref> would also have been held on Thursday 7 May 2020.\n\nUPDATE # On Friday, March 13th, the UK Government announced that ALL May-elections<ref name=\"MAY-Elections-Cancelled\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51876269/ |title=BBC - Coronavirus: English local elections postponed for a year |work=BBC News |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 }}</ref> will be postponed for a year, in response to the ongoing Coronavirus: outbreak.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Background==\nBefore the (Postponed) election [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] had a majority of 26 councillors, [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] had 9 councillors<ref name=\"HBC-Councillors\">{{Cite web|url=https://democracy.hyndburnbc.gov.uk/mgMemberIndex.aspx?FN=PARTY&VW=LIST&PIC=0 |title=Hyndburn Borough Council - Your councillors by political party |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=The Hyndburn Borough Council}}</ref>\n\nLabour would have been defending 10-seats with Conservatives defending 2-seats.\n\nAs a result, the composition of the council's 35 seats will remain UNCHANGED, until elections are re-scheduled, due in May 2021 (TBC) -\n\n*[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] 26\n*[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] 9\n\nNB: Four (of 16) Council wards, where seats would NOT have been up for re-election in 2020, included the following wards - Clayton Le Moors, Huncoat, Immanuel in Oswaldtwistle and Milnshaw in Accrington. However, as there was ALSO an election for Lancashire's next Police and Crime Commissioner, polling stations in those Four wards would have ALSO been OPEN.\n\nPrevious Councillors who were looking to Stand-Down in the May 2020 election included - Tony Dobson (Con) (Barnfield), Stephanie Haworth (Lab) (Overton)\n\nUPDATE #  Sadly, Councillor Tony Dobson (Con) (Barnfield), suddenly died on Monday, March 30th - as such his seat will probably by left 'vacant' as no by-elections will be called during the Coronavirus 'Lockdown'.\n\n==Ward Councillors==\n\nElected in May 2016, these Ward Councillors were expected to serve just a full FOUR-YEAR term, but would be required to serve another 12-Months, until the Postponed elections have been re-scheduled, due in May 2021 (TBC).\n\n===Altham